        "trailText":"<p>The lobbying bill could have disastrous consequences</p>",
        "headline":"Lobbying bill leaves charities and religious groups in anxious wait",
        "body":"<p>As the controversial lobbying bill shoots through parliament at alarming speed, charities have been left further confused over the murky overlap between charitable activity and political campaigning.</p><p>Earlier this month, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/20/allies-fight-lobbying-bill\">the bill exited the House of Commons in a state that left many charities remainingdissatisfied.</a> Graham Allen MP, chair of the <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/political-and-constitutional-reform-committee/\">Political and Constitutional Select Committee</a>, had tabled two amendments. One to financial thresholds for charitable spending and another to prevent charity campaigning being restricted if the primary purpose of an organisation's expenditure is not party political. Both these amendments were narrowly defeated.</p><p>The bill now being considered more than halves the existing thresholds above which third parties such as charities have to register with the Electoral Commission. Total campaign spending in the year before an election is also cut by up to 70%.</p><p>The bill proposes a broader definition of election campaigning and materials, which could stymie free speech for charities in the run-up to an election. Smaller charities could be penalised for legitimate daily activities such as campaigning and advocacy work around election time. And charities whose campaigns inadvertently become party political hot issues could also be prosecuted. Some commentators believe this is a cynical government attempt to gag third-sector dissent.</p><p>Elizabeth Chamberlain, senior campaigner at the <a href=\"http://www.ncvo-vol.org.uk/\">National Council for Voluntary Organisations</a>, says the bill has left charities in &quot;a very unclear and ambiguous situation with lots of questions unanswered, making it very difficult for them to plan any activity in the run up to an election&quot;.</p><p>Individual charities are also upset. <a href=\"http://www.foe.co.uk/\">Friends of the Earth</a> senior campaigner Liz Hutchins says the government has &quot;failed to listen to voluntary organisations about the lobbying bill&quot;.</p><p>Faith groups sent the government a joint open letter stating that the bill did not safeguard the activities of religious organisations and that there was a &quot;very real risk&quot; that non-biased activity would be affected.</p><p>&quot;As Quakers, we find our faith often calls us to speak out in the world and seek social change; we remain concerned that this bill will prevent us practising this key element of our faith,&quot; says Paul Parker, recording clerk for Quakers in Britain.</p><p>And while the focus has so far been on England, the very low spending thresholds set out for the devolved countries are a real cause for concern. In Scotland, the spending threshold for campaigning will plunge from &pound;108,000 to &pound;35,000. Ruchir Shah, policy manager for the <a href=\"http://www.scvo.org.uk/\">Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations</a>, says this will have a big impact, especially when compared to England. &quot;Given that salary costs are included, the very tight &pound;35,000 in Scotland automatically puts a Scottish organisation at a disadvantage compared to &pound;300,000 for a similarly sized organisation in England,&quot; he says.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.jmt.org/\">The John Muir Trust</a>, a UK conservation charity, is feeling the effects. Because half of its work centres around the wild lands of Scotland, it is subject to devolved Scottish legislation, which caps campaigning at &pound;35,000. &quot;Immediately that's knocked out our staff costs before we've printed a leaflet or spent any other money or attended conferences,&quot; says spokesperson Alan McCombes.</p><p>He also worries that if a Scottish political party endorses its wildlife campaign – an issue that cuts across political divisions – the charity could be penalised. &quot;What if a political party decided to put [our wildlife campaign] in their manifesto? Would that mean our entire wildland campaign at the heart of the organisation would have to be put on hold for a year?&quot;</p><p><strong>This content is brought to you by Guardian Professional. </strong><a href=\"https://register.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector/\" title=\"\"><strong>Join the voluntary sector network</strong></a><strong> for analysis, best practice and the latest job opportunities</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420378771|2013-11-11T15:34:05Z|08519e5147e1c76e3d36f8ce246e4c3ba6ecf771 -->",
